engers on the <i>Mayflower</i> in 1621; they were joined two years later by Francis's wife and other children. In the words of William Bradford, he lived long enough ‘to see his children's children have children’."],"variants":[{"name":"Cook","meanings":["English: occupational name for a cook, a seller of cooked meats, or a keeper of an eating house, from Middle English <i>cok</i>, <i>coke</i>, <i>cook</i>, <i>couk</i>, <i>cuk(e)</i> (Old English <i>cōc</i>) ‘cook’ or ‘seller of cooked foods’. See also   Kew  .","Irish and Scottish: usually identical in origin with the English name (see 1 above), but in some cases a shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Cúg</b> ‘son of Hugo’ (see   McCook  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of various European surnames meaning ‘cook’, such as German and Jewish   Koch  , Dutch   Kook  , Polish <b>Kucharz</b> and   Kucharczyk  , Slovenian and Croatian   Kuhar  , North German   Kuk  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Albert Cooke was born in 1179, in Leicestershire, England, his father, Sir William Cooke, was 24 and his mother, Jane Aurcomb, was 19. He married Guerin Warin in 1200, in Leicestershire, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died in 1210, in his hometown, at the age of 31."},"et":{"1179–1210":"1179–1210","1181–Male":"1181–Surnud","1183–Female":"1183–Surnud","1182–1215":"1182–1215","1171–Female":"1171–Surnud","1202–Male":"1202–Surnud","1203–1330":"1203–1330","1205–1275":"1205–1275","1200–1230":"1200–1230","1155–1193":"1155–1193","1160–1201":"1160–1201","1275":"1275","1330":"1330","1230":"1230","1183":"1183","1193":"1193","1160":"1160","1171":"1171","1182":"1182","1181":"1181","1205":"1205","1215":"1215","1203":"1203","1202":"1202","1179":"1179","1201":"1201","1200":"1200","1178":"1178","1210":"1210","1155":"1155","Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, England","Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincoln, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Leicestshire, England":"Leicestershire, Inglisma